# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: death
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] The **1887 Yellow River flood** in the Qing Dynasty began in late September 1887 and killed at least 930,000 people.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] It was the single deadliest flood in Chinese history, as well as one of the largest natural disasters by death toll in recorded history.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] For many centuries, farmers living near the Yellow River, China had built dikes to contain the river which flowed higher over time because of silt deposition on the riverbed.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] In 1887, this rising river, swollen by days of heavy rain, overcame the dikes on or around September 28, causing a massive flood.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] Since there is no international unit to measure a flood's strength, it is usually classified by the extent of the damage done, depth of the water, and the number of casualties.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] The water of the Yellow River is generally thought to have broken through the dikes in Huayuankou, near the city of Zhengzhou in Henan province.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] Owing to the low-lying plains near the area, the flood spread very quickly throughout Northern China, covering an estimated 50,000 square miles (130,000 km2), swamping agricultural settlements and commercial centers.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] After the flood, two million were left homeless.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] The resulting pandemic and lack of basic essentials claimed as many lives as those lost directly to the flood.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] It was one of the worst floods in history, though the later 1931 Yangtze-Huai River flood may have killed as many as four million.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] The highest estimated death toll is 2,000,000.
[src:death/1887-yellow-river-flood] The lowest estimated death toll was 900,000.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The **1931 China floods**, or the **1931 Yangtze–Huai River floods**, was a devastating flood that occurred from June to August 1931 in China, hitting major cities such as Wuhan, Nanjing and beyond, and eventually culminated in a dike breach along Lake Gaoyou on 25 August 1931.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] A cholera epidemic in the subsequent year, from May 1932, was officially reported to have 31,974 deaths and 100,666 cases.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] From 1928 to 1931 China was afflicted by a long drought.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The subsequent winter of 1930–31 was particularly harsh, creating large deposits of snow and ice in mountainous areas.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] In early 1931, melting snow and ice flowed downstream and arrived in the middle course of the Yangtze during a period of heavy spring rain.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Ordinarily, the region experienced three periods of high water during the spring, summer and autumn, respectively; however, in early 1931, there was a single continuous deluge.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] By June, those living in low areas had already been forced to abandon their homes.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The summer was also characterized by extreme cyclonic activity.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] In July of that year alone, nine cyclones hit the region, which was significantly above the average of two per year.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Four weather stations along the Yangtze River reported rain totaling over 600 mm (24 in) for the month.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The water flowing through the Yangtze reached its highest level since record-keeping began in the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] That autumn, further heavy rain added to the problem and some rivers did not return to their normal courses until November.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The floods inundated approximately 180,000 square kilometres (69,000 sq mi) – an area equivalent in size to England and half of Scotland, or the states of New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut combined.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The high-water mark recorded on 19 August at Hankou in Wuhan showed water levels 16 m (53 ft) above the average, an average of 1.7 m (5.6 ft) above the Shanghai Bund.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] In Chinese, this event is commonly known as 江淮水灾, which roughly translates to "Yangtze-Huai Flood Disaster".
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Waterways throughout much of the country were inundated, particularly the Yellow River and Grand Canal.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The eight most seriously affected provinces were Anhui, Hubei, Hunan, Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Jiangxi, Henan and Shandong.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Beyond the core flood zone, areas as far south as Guangdong, as far north as Manchuria, and as far west as Sichuan were also inundated.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] This flood is frequently featured in the list of disasters in China by death toll, sometimes topping lists of the world's deadliest natural disasters.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] At the time the government estimated that 25 million people had been affected by the flood.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Historians since have suggested that the true number may have been as many as 53 million.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Contemporary studies conducted by John Lossing Buck allege that at least 150,000 people had drowned in the first few months of the flood, with hundreds of thousands more dying of starvation and disease over the following year.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Using contemporary media reports, Chinese historians led by Li Wenhai have calculated the death toll at 422,420.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Some Western sources allege that the death toll was between 3.7 and 4 million people based on their own claims of famine and disease.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The Tanka people who traditionally live on boats along the Yangtze suffered greatly from the flooding.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The flood destroyed vast swaths of housing and farmland.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Throughout the entire Yangtze Valley, around 15% of the wheat and rice crops were destroyed, with the proportion being much higher in the flood-affected areas.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The disaster also caused an economic shock with the price of vital commodities rising rapidly.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The combined ecological and economic impacts of the disaster caused many areas to descend into famine.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] With no food, people were reduced to eating tree bark, weeds, and earth.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Some sold their children to survive, while others resorted to cannibalism.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The most lethal effect of the flood was the diseases that swept through the refugee population due to displacement, overcrowding, and the breakdown of sanitation.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] These included cholera, measles, malaria, dysentery, and schistosomiasis.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] As well as inundating rural areas, the flood caused widespread destruction to a number of cities.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Refugees had been arriving in the city of Wuhan since the late spring.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] When the city itself was inundated in the early summer and after a catastrophic dike failure at just before 6:00 AM on 27 July, around 782,189 urban citizens and rural refugees were left homeless.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The flood covered an area of 83 square kilometres (32 sq mi) and the city was flooded under many feet of water for close to three months.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Large numbers gathered on flood islands throughout the city, with 30,000 sheltering on a railway embankment in central Hankou.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] With little food and a complete breakdown in sanitation, thousands soon began to succumb to diseases.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The city of Nanjing, then the capital of Republican China, was also severely affected by the disaster.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] One of the most disastrous single events during the flood occurred on 25 August 1931, when the water rushing through the Grand Canal washed away dikes near Gaoyou Lake.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] In Gaoyou County alone, 18,000 people drowned and 58,000 died due to famine and diseases the following year.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Thomas Harnsberger, a missionary of the Presbyterian Church in Taizhou, Jiangsu, was one of the two central figures (alongside General Wang Shuxiang, a PhD in hydraulics) who supervised the rebuilding of the dikes at Lake Gaoyou, as well as securing the funds for it.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] However, the flood remains widely unknown to the Chinese.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Steve Harnsberger, the grandson of Thomas Harnsberger, wrote in 2007, "The 1931 flood killed 15 times the number of people lost in the Indonesian tsunamis of December 2004, and yet scarcely a word has been written of it.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] History focused instead on other disasters that year.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The 1931 flood was one of the first major tests for the Kuomintang Government.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] As the scale of the disaster became apparent, the government established the National Flood Relief Commission under the auspices of T.V.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Soong, a prominent politician in the Kuomintang and brother-in-law of Chiang Kai-shek.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The commission employed a range of Chinese and foreign experts, including figures such as famous epidemiologist Wu Liande, health minister Liu Ruiheng, public health worker John Grant, and hydraulic engineer Oliver Todd.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] It also secured the assistance of the League of Nations.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Even the famous aviators Charles Lindbergh and his wife Anne Lindbergh became involved, as they were commissioned to conduct an aerial survey of the flood zone.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Although Song Ziwen remained the head of the commission, the day-to-day running the relief effort was entrusted to John Hope Simpson, a British refugee expert.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Charity poured in to help with the relief effort from throughout the world, with overseas Chinese communities in Southeast Asia being particularly generous.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] In the United States, the celebrated author Pearl Buck wrote short stories to encourage charitable donations.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The relief effort became much more difficult following the Japanese invasion of Manchuria in the autumn of 1931, which caused the Chinese bond market to collapse.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Eventually, the government managed to secure a large loan of wheat and flour from the United States.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] In the wake of the disaster, the government set up organizations such as the Huai River Conservancy Commission to address flood problems.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] However, due to a lack of funding and the chaos of the Second Sino-Japanese War and the subsequent Chinese Civil War, the various commissions were only able to construct small dams along the Yangtze River.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] As part of an anti-superstition campaign by the Kuomintang Government, a Dragon King Temple was demolished in Wuhan shortly before the flood-hit.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] This coincidence led to widespread discontent afterwards, as many locals linked the disaster to the anger of Dragon King, a rainmaking deity.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] As a response, prominent officials, including He Baohua, mayor of Wuhan, and Xia Douyin, then the local garrison commander and later governor of Hubei Province, held ritual ceremonies and kowtowed to the deity.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Meanwhile, many believed that evacuation efforts were hindered by superstition.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] According to a contemporary report, thousands "are convinced that Hankow is doomed and refuse to help themselves or be helped.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] In 1953, after the end of the Chinese Civil War, Chinese Communist Party leader Mao Zedong travelled to areas neighbouring the Yangtze River to promote the Three Gorges Dam flood control project.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] "The Socialist Three Gorges Dam project should excel other major projects in Chinese history such as Qin Shi Huang's Great Wall and Sui Yang Di's Grand Canal", he stated.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Scientists and officials who raised doubts, such as Chen Mingshu, were persecuted as rightists.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] Li Siguang, a prominent scientist and minister of geological resources, told Mao he would commit suicide if he could not stop the construction of the dam.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The project did not move beyond the planning stage in Mao's time, due to a lack of resources, rising Sino-Soviet tensions and the disruptions of the Great Leap Forward.
[src:death/1931-china-floods] The project was restarted in the 1980s, and the hydroelectric Three Gorges Dam began full operation in 2012, becoming the world's largest power station in terms of installed capacity.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The **1970 Bhola cyclone**, also known as the **Great Cyclone of 1970** or simply the **Bhola Cyclone**, was the deadliest tropical cyclone on record, as well as one of the deadliest humanitarian disasters ever recorded.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] It struck East Pakistan (present-day Bangladesh) and India's West Bengal on 12 November 1970.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] At least 300,000 people died in the storm, possibly as many as 500,000, primarily as a result of the storm surge that flooded much of the low-lying islands of the Ganges Delta.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Bhola cyclone was the sixth and strongest cyclonic storm of the 1970 North Indian Ocean cyclone season.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The cyclone formed over the central Bay of Bengal on 8 November and travelled northward, intensifying as it did so.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] It reached its peak with winds of 185 km/h (115 mph) on 10 November, and made landfall on the coast of East Pakistan on the following afternoon.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The storm surge devastated many of the offshore islands, wiping out villages and destroying crops throughout the region.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In the most severely affected upazila Tazumuddin, over 45% of the population of 167,000 were killed by the storm.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Pakistani government, led by junta leader General Yahya Khan, was criticized for its delayed handling of relief operations following the storm, both by local political leaders in East Pakistan and by the international media.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] On 1 November, Tropical Storm Nora developed over the South China Sea, in the West Pacific Ocean.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The system lasted for four days before degenerating into a remnant low over the Gulf of Thailand on 4 November, and subsequently moved west over the Malay Peninsula the next day.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The remnants of this system contributed to the development of a new depression in the central Bay of Bengal on the morning of 8 November.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The depression intensified as it moved slowly northward, and the India Meteorological Department upgraded it to a cyclonic storm the next day.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] No country in the region had ever named tropical cyclones during this time, so no new identity was given.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The storm became nearly stationary that evening near 14°30′N 87°00′E﻿ / ﻿14.5°N 87°E﻿ / 14.5; 87, but began to accelerate toward the north on 10 November.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The storm further intensified into a severe cyclonic storm on 11 November and began to turn towards the northeast as it approached the head of the bay.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] It developed a clear eye and reached its peak intensity later that day, with three-minute sustained winds of 185 km/h (115 mph), one-minute sustained winds of 240 km/h (150 mph), and a central pressure of 960 hPa.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The cyclone made landfall on the East Pakistan coastline during the evening of 12 November, around the same time as the local high tide.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Once over land, the system began to weaken; the storm degraded to a cyclonic storm on 13 November, when it was about 100 km (62 mi) south-southeast of Agartala.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The storm then rapidly weakened into a remnant low over southern Assam that evening.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] There is some question as to how much of the information about the cyclone said to have been received by Indian weather authorities was transmitted to East Pakistan authorities.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] This is because the Indian and East Pakistani weather services may not have shared information given the Indo-Pakistani friction at the time.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A large part of the population was reportedly taken by surprise by the storm.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] There were indications that East Pakistan's storm warning system was not used properly.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Pakistan Meteorological Department issued a report calling for "danger preparedness" in the vulnerable coastal regions during the day on 12 November.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] As the storm neared the coast, a "great danger signal" was broadcast on Radio Pakistan.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Survivors later said that this meant little to them, but that they had recognised a No.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] 1 warning signal as representing the greatest possible threat.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Following two previously destructive cyclones in October 1960, which killed at least 16,000 people in East Pakistan, the Pakistani central government contacted the American government for assistance in developing a system to avert future disasters.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Gordon Dunn, the director of the National Hurricane Center at the time, carried out a detailed study and submitted his report in 1961.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] However, the central government did not carry out all the recommendations Dunn had listed.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Although the North Indian Ocean is the least active of the tropical cyclone basins, the coast of the Bay of Bengal is particularly vulnerable to the effects of tropical cyclones.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The exact death toll from the Bhola cyclone remains unknown, but at least 300,000 fatalities were associated with the storm, possibly as many as 500,000.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Bhola cyclone is the deadliest tropical cyclone on record and also one of the deadliest natural disasters in modern history.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A comparable number of people died as a result of the 1976 Tangshan earthquake, the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake, and the 2010 Haiti earthquake, but because of uncertainty in the number of deaths in all four disasters, it may never be known which one was the deadliest.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The meteorological station in Chittagong, 95 km (59 mi) to the east of where the storm made landfall, recorded winds of 144 km/h (89 mph) before its anemometer was blown off at about 2200 UTC on 12 November.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A ship anchored in the port in the same area recorded a peak gust of 222 km/h (138 mph) about 45 minutes later.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] As the storm made landfall, it caused a 10-metre (33 ft) high storm surge at the Ganges Delta.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In the port at Chittagong, the storm tide peaked at about 4 m (13 ft) above the average sea level, 1.2 m (3.9 ft) of which was the storm surge.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Radio Pakistan reported that there were no survivors on the thirteen islands near Chittagong.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A flight over the area showed the devastation was complete throughout the southern half of Bhola Island, and the rice crops of Bhola Island, Hatia Island and the nearby mainland coastline were destroyed.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Several seagoing vessels in the ports of Chittagong and Mongla were reported damaged, and the airports at Chittagong and Cox's Bazar were under 1 m (3.3 ft) of water for several hours.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Over 3.6 million people were directly affected by the cyclone, and the total damage from the storm was estimated at US$86.4 million (US$701 million in 2024).
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The survivors claimed that approximately 85% of homes in the area were destroyed or severely damaged, with the greatest destruction occurring along the coast.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Ninety percent of marine fishermen in the region suffered heavy losses, including the destruction of 9,000 offshore fishing boats.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Of the 77,000 onshore fishermen, 46,000 were killed by the cyclone, and 40% of the survivors were affected severely.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In total, approximately 65% of the fishing capacity of the coastal region was destroyed by the storm, in a region where about 80% of the protein consumed comes from fish.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Agricultural damage was similarly severe with the loss of US$63 million worth of crops and 280,000 cattle.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Three months after the storm, 75% of the population was receiving food from relief workers, and over 150,000 relied upon aid for half of their food.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Bhola Cyclone would also lead to increased cholera and typhoid cases in the region due to the contamination of the water supply in the storm.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Many attempts to send aid to the region were impeded by the prevalent cholera, and as a result, medical aid was delayed.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The cyclone brought widespread rain to the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, with very heavy rain falling in places on 8–9 November.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Port Blair recorded 130 mm (5.1 in) of rain on 8 November, and there were a number of floods on the islands.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] MV *Mahajagmitra*, a 5,500-ton freighter en route from Calcutta to Kuwait, was sunk by the storm on 12 November with the loss of all fifty people on board.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The ship sent out a distress signal and reported experiencing hurricane-force winds before it sank.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] There was also widespread rain in West Bengal and southern Assam.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The rain caused damage to housing and crops in both Indian states, with the worst damage occurring in the southernmost districts.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Two medical relief surveys were carried out by the Pakistan-SEATO Cholera Research Laboratory: the first in November and the second in February and March.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The purpose of the first survey was to establish the immediate medical needs in the affected regions.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The second, more detailed, survey was designed as the basis for long-term relief and recovery planning.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In the second survey, approximately 1.4% of the area's population was studied.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The first survey concluded that the surface water in most of the affected regions had a comparable salt content to that drawn from wells, except in Sudharam, where the water was almost undrinkable with a salt content of up to 0.5%.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The mortality was estimated at 14.2%—equivalent to a death toll of 240,000.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Cyclone-related morbidity was generally restricted to minor injuries, but a phenomenon dubbed "cyclone syndrome" was observed.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] This consisted of severe abrasions on the limbs and chest caused by survivors clinging to trees to withstand the storm surge.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Initially, there were fears of an outbreak of cholera and typhoid fever in the weeks following the storm, but the survey found no evidence of an epidemic of cholera, smallpox, or any other disease in the region affected by the storm.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Excluding these groups reduced the risk of hearsay and exaggeration.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The survey concluded that the overall death toll was, at minimum, 224,000.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The worst effects were felt in Tazumuddin, where the mortality was 46.3%, corresponding to approximately 80,000 deaths in the thana alone.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The mean mortality throughout the affected region was 16.5%.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The results showed that the highest survival rate was for adult males aged 15–49, while more than half the deaths were children under age 10, who only formed a third of the pre-cyclone population.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] This suggests that the young, old, and sick were at the highest risk of perishing in the cyclone and its storm surge.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In the months after the storm, the mortality of the middle-aged was lower in the cyclone area than in the control region, near Dhaka.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] This reflected the storm's toll on the less healthy individuals.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The days after the storm struck the coast, three Pakistani gunboats and a hospital ship carrying medical personnel and supplies left Chittagong for the islands of Hatiya, Sandwip, and Kutubdia.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Teams from the Pakistani Army reached many of the stricken areas in the two days following the landfall of the cyclone.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] President Khan visited East Pakistan on the way back from a trip to China.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In a press conference in Dhaka, Khan accepted the government had made "slips" and "mistakes" in their relief effort for the cyclone victims of then East Pakistan (now Bangladesh), but he insisted that "everything was done within the limits of the Government." He then returned to Rawalpindi.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] No West Pakistani political leaders visited the East.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In the ten and a half days following the cyclone, one military transport aircraft and three crop-dusting aircraft were assigned to relief work by the Pakistani central government.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The central government said it was unable to transfer military helicopters from West Pakistan as the Indian government did not grant clearance to cross the intervening Indian territory, a charge the Indian government denied.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] By 24 November, the central government had allocated a further US$116 million to finance relief operations in the disaster area.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Khan arrived in Dhaka to take charge of the relief operations on 24 November.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The governor of East Pakistan, Vice Admiral S.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Ahsan, denied charges that the armed forces had not acted quickly enough and said supplies were reaching all parts of the disaster area except for some small pockets.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Khan said there was a lack of understanding of the magnitude of the disaster.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] He also said that the 1970 general election slated for 7 December would take place on time, although eight or nine of the worst affected districts might experience delays, denying rumours that the election would be postponed.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] As the conflict between East and West Pakistan developed in March 1971, the Dhaka offices of the two government organisations directly involved in relief efforts were closed for at least two weeks, first by a general strike and then by a ban on government work in East Pakistan by the Awami League.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Relief work continued in the field, but the long-term planning was curtailed.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Political leaders in East Pakistan were deeply critical of the central government's initial response to the disaster.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A statement released by eleven East Pakistan politicians ten days after the storm charged the government with "gross neglect, callous indifference and utter indifference".
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] They also accused President Khan of playing down the news coverage.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] On November 19, students held a march in Dhaka in protest of the speed of the government response, and Maulana Abdul Hamid Khan Bhashani addressed a rally of 50,000 people on 24 November, when he accused the president of inefficiency and demanded his resignation.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Khan's political opponents in West Pakistan accused him of bungling the efforts, and some demanded his resignation.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Awami League leader Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman described the destruction caused by the cyclone as akin to a "Holocaust" and condemned the military junta's response as "criminal negligence".
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Pakistan Red Crescent began to operate independently of the central government as the result of a dispute that arose after the Red Crescent took possession of twenty rafts donated by the British Red Cross.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A pesticide company had to wait two days before it received permission for two of its crop dusters, which were already in the country, to carry out supply drops in the affected regions.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The central government only deployed a single helicopter to relief operations, with Khan later stating that there was no point in deploying any helicopters from West Pakistan as they were unable to carry supplies.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A reporter for the *Pakistan Observer* spent a week in the worst-hit areas in early January 1971 and saw none of the tents supplied by relief agencies being used to house survivors and commented that the grants for building new houses were insufficient.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A spokesman said families who were made homeless by the cyclone were receiving up to 250 rupees (US$55 in 1971; equivalent to $341 in 2018) to rebuild, but that resources were scarce and he feared the survivors would "eat the cash".
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Due to the poor handling and the destructive aftermath of the Bhola Cyclone, leftist parties in both East and West Pakistan boycotted the 1970 Pakistani general election.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] This allowed the Awami League, headed by Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, to win in a landslide victory.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The elections for nine national assembly and eighteen provincial assembly seats had to be postponed until January 18 as a result of the storm.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The central government's handling of the relief efforts helped exacerbate the bitterness felt in East Pakistan, swelling the resistance movement there.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Funds only slowly got through, and transport was slow in bringing supplies to the devastated regions.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] As tensions increased in March 1971, foreign personnel evacuated because of fears of violence.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The situation deteriorated further and evolved into the subsequent genocide.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] India became one of the first nations to offer aid to Pakistan, despite the generally poor relations between the two countries, and by the end of November had pledged US$1.3 million ($11 million in 2025) of assistance for the relief efforts.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Pakistani central government refused to allow the Indians to send supplies into East Pakistan by air, forcing them to be transported slowly by road instead.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Indian government also said that the Pakistanis refused an offer of military aircraft, helicopters, and boats from West Bengal to assist in the relief operation.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Six helicopters – two at an aid mission in Nepal and four from the U.S. – were also sent.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Some 200,000 tons of wheat were shipped from the U.S. to the stricken region.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] By the end of November, there were 38 helicopters operating in the disaster area, ten of which were British and ten American.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Americans had provided about fifty small boats and the British seventy for supply distribution.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] CARE halted aid shipments to East Pakistan the week after the cyclone hit because of unwillingness to let the Pakistani central government handle distribution.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] However, by January 1971, they had reached an agreement to construct 24,000 cement brick houses at a cost of about $1.2 million ($10 million in 2025).
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] American concerns about delays by the central government in determining how the relief should be used meant that US$7.5 million ($62 million in 2025) of relief granted by the United States Congress had not been handed over in March.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Much of the money was earmarked to be spent on constructing cyclone shelters and rebuilding housing.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The American Peace Corps offered to send volunteers but was rebuffed by the central government.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A Royal Navy task force, centred on HMS *Intrepid* and HMS *Triumph*, left Singapore for the Bay of Bengal to assist with the relief efforts.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] They carried eight helicopters and eight landing craft, as well as rescue teams and supplies.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Fifty soldiers and two helicopters were flown in ahead of the ships to survey the disaster area and bring relief work.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The task force arrived off the East Pakistan coast on 24 November, and the 650 troops aboard the ships immediately began using landing craft to deliver supplies to offshore islands.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] An appeal by the British Disasters Emergency Committee raised about £1.5 million (£21 million in 2025) for disaster relief in East Pakistan.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Canadian government pledged C$2 million (C$16 million in 2025) of assistance.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] France and West Germany both sent helicopters and various supplies worth US$1.3 million.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Pope Paul VI announced that he would visit Dhaka during a visit to the Far East and urged people to pray for the victims of the disaster.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Vatican later contributed US$100,000 to the relief efforts.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] By the start of 1971, four Soviet helicopters were still operating in the region transporting essential supplies to hard-hit areas.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Soviet aircraft, which had drawn criticism from Bengalis, replaced the British and American helicopters that had operated immediately after the cyclone.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The government of Singapore sent a military medical mission to East Pakistan which arrived at Chittagong on 1 December.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] They were then deployed to Sandwip where they treated nearly 27,000 people and carried out a smallpox vaccination effort.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The mission returned to Singapore on 22 December, after bringing about $50,000 worth of medical supplies and fifteen tons of food for the victims of the storm.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Japanese cabinet approved a total of US$1.65 million of relief funds in December.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Japanese government had previously drawn criticism for only donating a small amount to relief work.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The first shipment of Chinese supplies was a planeload of 500,000 doses of cholera vaccine, which was not necessary as the country had adequate stocks.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The Chinese government sent US$1.2 million in cash to Pakistan.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Mohammad Reza Pahlavi declared that the disaster was also an Iranian one and responded by sending two planeloads of supplies within a few days of the cyclone striking.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Many smaller, poorer Asian nations sent nominal amounts of aid.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The United Nations donated US$2.1 million in food and cash, while UNICEF began a drive to raise a further million.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] UNICEF helped to re-establish water supplies in the wake of the storm, repairing over 11,000 wells in the months following the storm.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] UN Secretary-General U Thant made appeals for aid for the victims of the cyclone and the civil war in August, in two separate relief programs.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] He said only about $4 million had been contributed towards immediate needs, well short of the target of US$29.2 million.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] By the end of November, the League of Red Cross Societies had collected US$3.5 million to supply aid to the victims of the disaster.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The World Bank estimated that it would cost US$185 million to reconstruct the area devastated by the storm.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The bank drew up a comprehensive recovery plan for the Pakistani government.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The plan included restoring housing, water supplies and infrastructure to their pre-storm state.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] It was designed to combine with a much larger ongoing flood-control and development program.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The bank provided US$25 million of credit to help rebuild the East Pakistan economy and to construct protective shelters in the region.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] This was the first time that the IDA had provided credit for reconstruction.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] By the start of December, nearly US$40 million had been raised for the relief efforts by the governments of 41 countries, organizations and private groups.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In 1971, ex-Beatle George Harrison and musician Ravi Shankar were inspired to organize The Concert for Bangladesh, in part from the Bhola cyclone, and from the civil war and genocide.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Although it was the first benefit concert of its type, it was extremely successful in raising money, aid, and awareness for the region's plight.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In December 1970, the League of Red Cross Societies drafted a plan for immediate use should a comparable event to the cyclone hit other "disaster prone countries".
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] A Red Cross official stated some of the relief workers sent to East Pakistan were poorly trained, and the organisation would compile a list of specialists.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The UN General Assembly adopted a proposal to improve its ability to provide aid to disaster-stricken countries.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In 1966, the Red Crescent had begun to support the development of a cyclone warning system, which developed into a Cyclone Preparedness Programme in 1972, today run by the government of Bangladesh and the Bangladesh Red Crescent Society.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] The programme's objectives are to raise public awareness of the risks of cyclones and to provide training to emergency personnel in the coastal regions of Bangladesh.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] In the thirty years after the 1970 cyclone, over 200 cyclone shelters were constructed in the coastal regions of Bangladesh.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] When the next destructive cyclone approached the country in 1991, volunteers from the Cyclone Preparedness Programme warned people of the cyclone two to three days before it struck land.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Over 350,000 people fled their homes to shelters and other brick structures, while others sought high ground.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] While the 1991 cyclone killed over 138,000 people, this was significantly less than the 1970 storm, partly because of the warnings sent out by the Cyclone Preparedness Programme.
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] However, the 1991 storm was significantly more destructive, causing US$1.5 billion (equivalent to $3.1 billion in 2024) compared to the 1970 storm's $86 million (equivalent to $536.97 million in 2024).
[src:death/1970-bhola-cyclone] Footage of the incident appeared in the film *Days of Fury* (1979), directed by Fred Warshofsky and hosted by Vincent Price.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] In August 1975, the Banqiao Dam and 61 others throughout Henan, China, collapsed following the landfall of Typhoon Nina.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The dam collapse created the third-deadliest flood in history which affected 12,000 km2 (3 million acres) with a total population of 10.15 million, including around 30 cities and counties, with estimates of the death toll ranging from 26,000 to 240,000.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The flood also caused the collapse of 5 million to 6.8 million houses.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The dam failure took place in the context of the Cultural Revolution.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Many of the dams that collapsed were originally constructed with the help of Soviet advisors.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Many were built during the Great Leap Forward.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The construction of the dams focused heavily on the goal of retaining water and overlooked their capacities to prevent floods, while the quality of the dams was also compromised due to the Great Leap Forward.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The Banqiao dam had been designed for a calculated one in a thousand year rainfall event of 300 mm per day; however, more than the normal yearly rainfall (1,060 mm) fell in just one day near the typhoon center.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The official documents of the disaster were declassified in 2005 by the Chinese government.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Starting in the early 1950s, three major reservoirs and dams, including the Banqiao, Shimantan and Baisha dams, were under construction in Zhumadian.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The long-term project, under the name of "Harness the Huai River", was launched to prevent flooding and to utilize the water for irrigation and generating electricity.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] At the time, Chinese construction workers had no experience with building major reservoirs and, as a result, the design and construction was completely under the guidance of experts from the Soviet Union.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The design of the dams overly focused on the purpose of water storage while overlooking the capacities of preventing floods.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Hydrological data was lacking, and the reservoir was designed to handle a 'once in 1000 years' 306 mm of daily rainfall and 530 mm of rainfall in 3 days.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] By 1953, the construction work at the three reservoirs was completed, but a "reinforcement" project on Banqiao and Shimantan dams was further carried out from 1955 to 1956 following the instructions of the Soviet Union.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] After renovations, the Banqiao dam was known as the "Iron Dam" to reflect its invincibility.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] After the Great Leap Forward was launched by Mao Zedong, over 100 dams were built in the Zhumadian region from 1957 to 1959.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Tan Zhenlin, then Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China, issued the guidelines on reservoir construction during his trip to Henan Province: "focusing on retaining water, building more small reservoirs".
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] At the time, "retaining more water" meant "more revolutionary".
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] On the other hand, the intense production of steel during the Great Leap Forward as well as the "Learn from Dazhai in agriculture" program launched by Mao severely damaged the ecosystem in the Zhumadian region.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The percentage of forest cover dropped drastically and land degradation was prevalent, which, according to most experts, were the major causes of floods.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Chen Xing, then chief engineer of the dam projects, opposed the ideas of constructing too many dams as well as prioritizing the goal of "retaining water".
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] He pointed out that the local geographical conditions made it unreasonable to overly emphasize the reservoir's function of water storage, because otherwise there was risk of creating serious floods and other disasters, such as alkalinization of farm land.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Nevertheless, Chen's warning was ignored and he was criticized for being a "rightist" and "opportunist"; he was subsequently removed from his post and was sent to Xinyang.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The collapse of the dams occurred during the Cultural Revolution (1966–1976), when most people were busy with the revolution and had little time with the dams while it was raining heavily.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] In fact, there were no resources or equipment available to prevent the flood.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] After the disaster, Xinhua journalist Zhang Guangyou (张广友) visited the area and interviewed several experts, who were afraid to express their opinions in public lest they be condemned for "questioning the Cultural Revolution" and "questioning Chairman Mao".
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] However, the experts told Zhang privately that the degradation and the damage to the ecosystem due to Mao's Great Leap Forward were the major causes of the collapse of the dams.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] According to testimonies from residents, the summer had been very dry that year, with a drought starting from July.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] On August 4, sudden heavy rain started, which would continue for the following days.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] In Queshan County, 1,100 mm of rain was measured over three days.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] By August 5, many smaller reservoirs already reached their storage limit.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] That same evening, Banqiao town, near the dam, started to flood.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] By the next day, the dam control office lost communication with upstream rainfall stations, as the phone switchboard had been flooded.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] When officials from Banqiao town reached Zhumadian to report on the situation, the concerns were dismissed as the dam was considered invincible.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] A request to open the dam was rejected because of the existing flooding in downstream areas.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] On August 7 the request was accepted, but the telegrams failed to reach the dam operators.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The sluice gates were not able to handle the overflow of water partially due to sedimentation blockage.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] At noon, local officials held an emergency meeting and found that no explosives or other equipment was available to speed up the water outflow.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] By 4 pm, another 13 hour rainstorm started.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] At 7 pm, residents of nearby downstream towns of Banqiao and Shahedian in Biyang County received evacuation notices, but those on the other side of the river in Suiping County did not.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] On August 7 at 21:30, the People's Liberation Army Unit 34450 (by name the 2nd Artillery Division in residence at Queshan county), which was deployed on the Banqiao Dam, sent the first dam failure warning via telegraph.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] On August 8, at 01:00, water at Banqiao crested at 117.94 m above sea level, or 0.3 m higher than the wave protection wall on the dam, and it failed.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The same storm caused the failure of 62 dams in total.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The runoff of Banqiao Dam was 13,000 m3 per second in vs.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Seven county seats, Suiping, Xiping, Ru'nan, Pingyu, Xincai, Luohe, and Linquan were inundated, as were thousands of square kilometers of countryside and countless communities.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Evacuation orders had not been fully delivered due to weather conditions and poor communications.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Telegraphs failed, signal flares fired by Unit 34450 were misunderstood, telephones were rare, and some messengers were caught by the flood.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] To protect other dams from failure, several flood diversion areas were evacuated and inundated, and several dams were deliberately destroyed by air strikes to release water in desired directions.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The Nihewa and Laowangpo flood diversion areas downstream of the dams soon exceeded their capacity and gave up part of their storage on August 8, forcing more flood diversion areas to begin to evacuate.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] By August 9, the rain had stopped but the floods continued.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The dikes on the Quan River collapsed in the evening of August 9, and the entire Linquan county in Fuyang, Anhui was inundated.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] As the Boshan Dam, with a capacity of 400 million m3, crested and the water released from the failures of Banqiao and Shimantan was rushing downstream, air strikes were made against several other dams to protect the Suya Lake dam, already holding 1.2 billion m3 of water.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] A total of 102 kilometers of the Jingguang Railway, a major artery from Beijing to Guangzhou, was cut for 48 days, as were other crucial communications lines.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Although 42,618 People's Liberation Army troops were deployed for disaster relief, all communication to and from the cities was cut.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] By August 13, the water level was still rising in Xincai and Pingyu, affecting 2 million people.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] On August 17, there were still over a million people trapped by the waters, most in Shangcai County, who relied on airdrops of food or lacked food entirely, and were unreachable by disaster relief workers.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] It was reported that half of the airdropped food fell into the water.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Epidemics and famine devastated the trapped survivors.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] In Runan County alone, 320,000 out of 500,000 residents needed medical attention due to suffering from dysentery, typhoid fever, hepatitis, colds, malaria, enteritis, encephalitis, high fever, trauma, poisoning, pink eye, and other conditions.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] In order to speed up the water drainage, the Bantai sluice gates near Xincai were blown up, as officials were forced to choose causing flooding in downstream Fuyang in Anhui, or exacerbating the number of victims in Henan.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] A further 1.5 million residents of Anhui were thus affected by the disaster.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The floods only fully receded two weeks later, revealing rotting corpses everywhere.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The damage to the Zhumadian area was estimated to be about CN¥3.5 billion (US$513 million).
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The Zhumadian government appealed to the whole nation for help, and received more than CN¥300 million (US$44,000,000) in donations.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] After the disaster, the Chinese Communist Party and the Chinese government remained silent to the public, while no media were allowed to make reports.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] In 1987, Yu Weimin (于为民), a journalist from *Henan Daily* wrote a book on the disaster, while in 1995 the news agency took the lead and published details about the disaster to the public.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] At the official level, *The Great Floods in China's History* (中国历史大洪水) revealed part of the information to the public for the first time; the book was prefaced by Qian Zhengying who served as the Minister of Water Resources of China in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The official documents of this disaster were considered a state secret until 2005 when they were declassified.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Scientists from China, Italy and the United States subsequently attended a seminar in Beijing, discussing the details.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] Unofficial figures reported that 85,600–240,000 people died as a result of the dam breaking, although the official figure is 26,000.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The Chinese government deems the dam failure a natural one as opposed to man-made disaster, with government sources placing an emphasis on the amount of rainfall as opposed to poor engineering and construction.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] *People's Daily* has maintained that the dam was designed to survive a once-in-1000-years flood (300 mm of rainfall per day) but a once-in-2000-years flood occurred in August 1975, following the collision of Typhoon Nina and a cold front.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] The typhoon was blocked for two days before its direction ultimately changed from northeastward to westward.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] As a result of this near stationary thunderstorm system, more than a year's worth of rain fell within 24 hours, which weather forecasts failed to predict.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] New records were set, at 1,060 millimetres (42 in) per day, exceeding the average annual precipitation of about 800 millimetres (31 in).
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] China Central Television reported that the typhoon disappeared from radar as it degraded.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] According to Xinhua, the forecast was for rainfall of 100 mm by the Beijing-based Central Meteorological Observatory.
[src:death/1975-banqiao-dam-failure] After the flood, a summit of National Flood Prevention and Reservoir Security at Zhengzhou, Henan was held by the Department of Water Conservancy and Electricity, and a nationwide reservoir security examination was performed.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Abortion continues to be a controversial subject in many societies on religious, moral, ethical, practical, and political grounds.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Though it has been banned and otherwise limited by law in many jurisdictions, abortions continue to be common in many areas, even where they are illegal.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] According to a 2007 study conducted by the Guttmacher Institute and the World Health Organization, abortion rates are similar in countries where the procedure is legal and in countries where it is not, due to unavailability of modern contraceptives in areas where abortion is illegal.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Also according to the study, the number of abortions worldwide is declining due to increased access to contraception.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Abortion has existed since ancient times, with natural abortifacients being found amongst a wide variety of tribal people and in most written sources.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The earliest known records of abortion techniques and general reproductive regulation date as far back as 2700 BC in China, and 1550 BC in Egypt.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Early texts contain little mention of abortion or abortion law.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] When it does appear, it is entailed in concerns about male property rights, preservation of social order, and the duty to produce fit citizens for the state or community.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The harshest penalties were generally reserved for a woman who procured an abortion against her husband's wishes, and for slaves who produced abortion in a woman of high status.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Religious texts often contained severe condemnations of abortion, recommending penance but seldom enforcing secular punishment.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] As a matter of common law in England and the United States, abortion was illegal anytime after quickening—when the movements of the fetus could first be felt by the woman.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Under the born alive rule, the fetus was not considered a "reasonable being" *in rerum natura*; and abortion was not treated as murder in English law.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In the 19th century, many Western countries began to codify abortion laws or place further restrictions on the practice.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Anti-abortion movements were led by a combination of groups opposed to abortion on moral grounds, and by medical professionals who were concerned about the danger presented by the procedure and the regular involvement of non-medical personnel in performing abortions.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Nevertheless, it became clear that illegal abortions continued to take place in large numbers even where abortions were rigorously restricted.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] It was difficult to obtain sufficient evidence to prosecute the women and abortion doctors, and judges and juries were often reluctant to convict.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] For example, Henry Morgentaler, a Canadian pro-choice advocate, was never convicted by a jury.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] He was acquitted by a jury in the 1973 court case, but the acquittal was overturned by five judges on the Quebec Court of Appeal in 1974.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] He went to prison, appealed, and was again acquitted.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In total, he served 10 months, suffering a heart attack while in solitary confinement.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Many were also outraged at the invasion of privacy and the medical problems resulting from abortions taking place illegally in medically dangerous circumstances.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Political movements soon coalesced around the legalization of abortion and liberalization of existing laws.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] By the first half of the 20th century, many countries had begun to liberalize abortion laws, at least when performed to protect the woman's life and in some cases on the woman's request.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Under Vladimir Lenin, the Soviet Union became the first modern state in legalizing abortions on request—the law was first introduced in the Russian SFSR in 1920, in the Ukrainian SSR in July 1921, and then in the whole country.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The Bolsheviks saw abortion as a social evil created by the capitalist system, which left women without the economic means to raise children, forcing them to perform abortions.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The Soviet state initially preserved the tsarist ban on abortion, which treated the practice as premeditated murder.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] However, abortion had been practiced by Russian women for decades and its incidence skyrocketed further as a result of the Russian Civil War, which had left the country economically devastated and made it extremely difficult for many people to have children.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The Soviet state recognized that banning abortion would not stop the practice because women would continue using the services of private abortionists.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In rural areas, these were often old women who had no medical training, which made their services very dangerous to women's health.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In November 1920, the Soviet government legalized abortion in state hospitals.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The state considered abortion as a temporary necessary evil, which would disappear in the future communist society, which would be able to provide for all the children conceived.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In 1936, Joseph Stalin placed prohibitions on abortions, which restricted them to medically recommended cases only, in order to increase population growth after the enormous loss of life in World War I and the Russian Civil War.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In the 1930s, several countries (Poland, Turkey, Denmark, Sweden, Iceland, Mexico) legalized abortion in some special cases (pregnancy from rape, threat to mother's health, fetal malformation).
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In Japan, abortion was legalized in 1948 by the Eugenic Protection Law, amended in May 1949 to allow abortions for economic reasons.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Abortion was legalized in 1952 in Yugoslavia (on a limited basis), and again in 1955 in the Soviet Union on request.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Some Soviet allies (Poland, Hungary, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Romania) legalized abortion in the late 1950s under pressure from the Soviets.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In the United Kingdom, the Abortion Act of 1967 clarified and prescribed abortions as legal up to 28 weeks (later reduced to 24 weeks).
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Other countries soon followed, including Canada (1969), the United States (1973 in most states, pursuant to *Roe v.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Supreme Court decision which legalized abortion nationwide until 2022), Tunisia and Denmark (1973), Austria (1974), France and Sweden (1975), New Zealand (1977), Italy (1978), the Netherlands (1984), and Belgium (1990).
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] However, these countries vary greatly in the circumstances under which abortion was to be permitted.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In 1975, the West German Supreme Court struck down a law legalizing abortion, holding that it contradicted the constitution's human rights guarantees.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In 1976, a law was adopted which enabled abortions up to 12 weeks.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The other schools hold intermediate positions. ...
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The penalty prescribed for an illegal abortion varies according to particular circumstances involved.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The table below lists in chronological order the United Nations member states that have legalized abortion on request in at least some initial part of the pregnancy, or that have fully decriminalized abortion.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] As of 2025, 67 countries have legalized or decriminalized abortion on request.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Where a country has legalized abortion on request, prohibited it, and legalized it again (e.g., former Soviet Union, Romania), only the later year is included.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Countries that result from the merger of states where abortion on request was legal at the moment of unification show the year when it became legal across the whole national territory (e.g., Germany, Vietnam).
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Similarly, countries where not all subnational jurisdictions have legalized abortion on request are not included, leading to the exclusion of Australia, Mexico, and the United Kingdom.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Countries where abortion on request was once legalized nationwide but has since been prohibited in at least part of the country, such as the United States and Poland, are also excluded.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Countries are counted even if they were not yet independent at the time.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The year refers to when the relevant law or judicial decision came into force, which may be different from the year when it was approved.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] There are no international or multinational treaties that deal directly with abortion but human rights law and international criminal law touch on the issues.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The Nuremberg Military Tribunal decided the case of *United States v Greifelt and Others* (1948) on the basis that abortion was a crime within its jurisdiction according to the law defining crimes against humanity and thus within its definition of murder and extermination.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The Catholic Church remains highly influential in Latin America, and opposes the legalisation of abortion.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The American Convention on Human Rights, which in 2013 had 23 Latin American parties, declares human life as commencing with conception.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In Latin America, abortion on request is only legal in Cuba (1965), Uruguay (2012), Argentina (2021), Colombia (2022) and in parts of Mexico.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Abortions are completely banned in the Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua, and only allowed in certain restricted circumstances in most other Latin American nations.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In the 2010 case of *A, B and C v Ireland*, the European Court of Human Rights found that the European Convention on Human Rights did not include a right to an abortion.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In the 2016 case of *Mellet v Ireland*, the UN HRC found Ireland's abortion laws violated the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights because Irish law banned abortion in cases of fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] While abortions are legal at least under certain conditions in almost all countries, these conditions vary widely.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] According to a United Nations (UN) report with data gathered up to 2019, abortion is allowed in 98% of countries in order to save a woman's life.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Other commonly accepted reasons are preserving physical (72%) or mental health (69%), in cases of rape or incest (61%), and in cases of fetal impairment (61%).
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Performing an abortion because of economic or social reasons is accepted in 37% of countries.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Performing abortion only on the basis of a woman's request is allowed in 34% of countries, including in Canada, most European countries and China.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The exact scope of each legal ground also varies.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] For example, the laws of some countries cite health risks and fetal impairment as general grounds for abortion and allow a broad interpretation of such terms in practice, while other countries restrict them to a specific list of medical conditions or subcategories.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Many countries that allow abortion have gestational limits for the procedure depending on the reason; with the majority being up to 12 weeks for abortion on request, up to 24 weeks for social, economic, rape, or incest reasons, and more for fetal impairment or threats to the woman's health or life.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] In some countries, additional procedures must be followed before the abortion can be carried out even if the basic grounds for it are met.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] How strictly all of the procedures dictated in the legislation are followed in practice is another matter.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] For example, in the United Kingdom, a Care Quality Commission's report in 2012 found that several NHS clinics were circumventing the law, using forms pre-signed by one doctor, thus allowing abortions to patients who only met with one doctor.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in all United Nations member states and United Nations General Assembly observer states and some countries with limited recognition.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] This table is mostly based on data compiled by the United Nations up to 2019, with some updates, additions and clarifications citing other sources.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in autonomous jurisdictions not included in the previous table.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Legal limits may not be directly comparable.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Limits may be expressed in trimesters, months, weeks of pregnancy (implantation), weeks from fertilization, or weeks from last menstrual period (LMP).
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] According to a report by Women on Waves, approximately 25% of the world's population lives in countries with "highly restrictive abortion laws"—that is, laws which either completely ban abortion, or allow it only to save the mother's life.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] This category includes several countries in Latin America, Africa, Asia and Oceania, as well as Andorra and Malta in Europe.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] El Salvador has some of the strictest abortion laws of any country.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Abortion under all circumstances, including rape, incest, and risk to the mother's health, is illegal.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Women can be criminalized and penalized to up to 40 years in prison after being found guilty of an abortion.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] El Salvador's abortion laws are so severe that miscarriages and stillbirths can sometimes be enough for conviction.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] The Inter-American Court has already ruled that El Salvador was responsible for the death of Manuela, who was sentenced to 30 years in prison in 2008 for aggravated homicide after suffering an obstetric emergency that resulted in her losing her pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Controversy over the beginning of pregnancy occurs in different contexts, particularly in a legal context, and is particularly discussed within the abortion debate from the point of measuring the gestational age of the pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] Pregnancy can be measured from a number of convenient points, including the day of last menstruation, ovulation, fertilization, implantation and chemical detection.
[src:death/abortion-law-p01] A common medical way to calculate gestational age is to measure pregnancy from the first day of the last menstrual cycle.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Exceptions in abortion laws occur either in countries where abortion is as a general rule illegal or in countries that have abortion on request with gestational limits.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] For example, if a country allows abortion on request until 12 weeks, it may create exceptions to this general gestation limit for later abortions in specific circumstances.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] There are a few exceptions commonly found in abortion laws.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Legal domains which do not have abortion on demand will often allow it when the health of the mother is at stake.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Laws allowing abortion in cases of rape or incest often differ.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Wade*, thirteen U.S. states allowed abortion in the case of either rape or incest, but only Mississippi permitted abortion of pregnancies due to rape, and no state permitted it for just incest.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Many countries allow abortion only through the first or second trimester, and some may allow abortion in cases of fetal defects, e.g., Down syndrome, or where the pregnancy is the result of a sexual crime.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Laws in some countries with liberal abortion laws protect access to abortion services.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Such legislation often seeks to guard abortion clinics against obstruction, vandalism, picketing, and other actions, or to protect patients and employees of such facilities from threats and harassment.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Other laws create a perimeter around a facility, known variously as a "buffer zone", "bubble zone", or "access zone", where demonstrations opposing abortion are not permitted.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Protests and other displays are restricted to a certain distance from the building, which varies depending on the law.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Similar zones have also been created to protect the homes of abortion providers and clinic staff.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Bubble zone laws are divided into "fixed" and "floating" categories.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] Fixed bubble zone laws apply to the static area around the facility itself, and floating laws to objects in transit, such as people or cars.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] On 3 November 2020, an association of 20 Kenyan charities urged the government of Kenya to withdraw from the Geneva Consensus Declaration (GCD), a US-led international accord that sought to limit access to abortion for girls and women around the world.
[src:death/abortion-law-p02] GCD was signed by 33 nations, on 22 October 2020.
[src:death/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:death/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:death/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:death/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:death/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:death/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:death/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:death/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:death/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:death/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:death/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:death/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:death/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:death/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:death/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:death/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:death/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:death/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:death/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:death/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:death/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:death/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:death/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:death/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:death/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:death/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:death/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:death/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:death/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:death/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:death/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:death/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:death/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:death/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:death/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:death/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:death/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:death/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:death/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:death/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:death/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:death/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:death/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:death/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:death/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:death/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:death/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:death/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:death/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:death/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:death/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:death/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:death/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:death/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:death/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:death/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:death/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:death/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:death/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:death/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:death/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:death/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:death/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:death/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:death/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:death/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:death/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:death/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:death/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:death/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:death/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:death/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:death/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:death/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:death/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:death/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:death/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:death/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:death/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:death/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The religions of this set share doctrinal, historical, and geographic overlap that contrast them with Indian religions, Iranian religions, and East Asian religions, although some smaller Abrahamic religions, such as the Baha'i Faith, are also Iranian religions.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, are the three largest Abrahamic religions, with Christianity and Islam being followed and adhered to by around half of the world's population.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] However, the term has been criticized by some scholars for reportedly oversimplifying cultural and doctrinal nuances between the different religions.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The term *Abrahamic religions* (and its variations) is a collective religious descriptor for similar and closely related elements shared by Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, as well as the smaller religions such as the Baháʼí Faith, the Druze faith, Rastafari, and Samaritanism.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] It features prominently in interfaith dialogue and civil discourse, as well as academic discourse.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The term appears for the first time in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Although historically the term *Abrahamic religions* was limited to just Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, restricting the category to these three religions has come under criticism.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The late-19th-century Baháʼí Faith has been characterized as Abrahamic, as it is a monotheistic religion that recognizes its own descent from Abraham.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The figure of Abraham is suggested as a common ground for Judaism, Christianity, Islam, as well as Samaritanism, the Druze Faith, the Baha'i Faith, and Rastafari and a hypothesized eschatological reconciliation of the seven religions.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Commonalities may include creation, revelation, and redemption, but such shared concepts vary significantly between and within the Abrahamic religions themselves.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Proponents of the term argue that all seven religions are united through the deity worshipped by Abraham.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Catholic scholar of Islam Louis Massignon argued that the phrase "Abrahamic religion" means that the religions come from one spiritual source.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The modern term comes from the plural form of a Quranic reference to *dīn Ibrāhīm* ("religion of Abraham").
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In Christianity, Paul the Apostle, in Romans 4:11–12, refers to Abraham as "father of all", including those "who have faith, circumcised or uncircumcised." From its founding, Islam likewise conceived of itself as the "religion of Abraham".
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Bahá’í scriptures state that the religion's founder, Baháʼu'lláh, descended from Abraham through his wife Keturah's sons.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The appropriateness of grouping Judaism, Christianity, and Islam as "Abrahamic religions" and related terms has been challenged.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Adam Dodds argues that the term "Abrahamic faiths", while helpful, can be misleading, as it conveys an unspecified historical and theological commonality that is problematic on closer examination.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] While there is commonality among the religions, their shared ancestry is mainly peripheral to their respective foundational theological claims, practices, and cultures, concealing irreconcilable differences.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The common Christian doctrines of Jesus's Incarnation, the Trinity, and the resurrection of Jesus, for example, are accepted in neither Judaism nor Islam.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Jewish tradition claims that the Twelve Tribes of Israel are descended from Abraham through his son Isaac and grandson Jacob, whose sons formed the nation of the Israelites in Canaan.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In its early stages, the Israelite religion (Yahwism) shares traits with the Canaanite religions of the Bronze Age; by the Iron Age, it had become distinct from other Canaanite religions as it shed polytheism for monolatry.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] They understood their relationship with their god, Yahweh, as a covenant and that the deity promised Abraham a permanent homeland.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The monolatrist nature of Yahwism was further developed in the period following the Babylonian captivity, eventually emerging as a firm religious movement of monotheism.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] With the Fall of Babylon, Judaism incorporated concepts such as messianism, belief in free will and judgement after death, conception of heaven and hell, angels and demons, among others, into their belief-system.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Christianity traces back their origin to the 1st century and refers to themselves as a continuation of Judaism (commonly referred to as the old covenant) initially led by Jesus.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] His followers viewed him as the Messiah, as in the Confession of Peter; after his crucifixion and death they came to view him as God incarnate, who was resurrected and will return at the end of time to judge the living and the dead and create an eternal Kingdom of God.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In the 1st century AD, under the Apostles of Jesus of Nazareth; Christianity spread widely.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Paul the Apostle interpreted the role of Abraham differently from the Jews of his time.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] While for the Jews, Abraham was considered a loyal monotheist in a polytheistic environment, Paul celebrates Abraham as a man who found faith in God before adhering to religious law.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In contrast to Judaism, adherence to religious law becomes associated with idolatry.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] While Christians fashioned their religion around Jesus of Nazareth, the siege of Jerusalem (70 CE), forced Jews to reconcile their belief-system with the destruction of the Second Temple and associated rituals.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] At this time, both Judaism and Christianity had to systematize their scriptures and beliefs, resulting in competing theologies both claiming Abrahamic heritage.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Christians could hardly dismiss the Hebrew scriptures as Jesus himself refers to them according to Christian reports, and parallels between Jesus and the Biblical stories of *creation* and *redemption* starting with Abraham in the *Book of Genesis*.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The distant God asserted by Jesus according to the Christians, created a form of dualism between Creator and creation and the doctrine of *Creatio ex nihilo*, which later heavily influenced Jewish and Islamic theology.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] By that, Christians established their own identity, distinct from both Greeks and Jews, as those who venerate and worship the deity of Jesus.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] After several periods of alternating persecution and relative peace *vis-à-vis* the Roman authorities under different administrations, Christianity became the state church of the Roman Empire in 380, but has been split into various churches from its beginning.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] An attempt was made by the Byzantine Empire to unify Christendom, but this formally failed with the East–West Schism of 1054.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In the 16th century, the birth and growth of Protestantism during the Reformation further split Christianity into many denominations.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Christianity remains culturally diverse in its Western and Eastern branches, Christianity played a prominent role in the development of Western civilization.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Islam is based on the teachings of the Quran.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Although it considers Muhammad to be the Seal of the prophets, Islam teaches that every prophet preached Islam, as the word *Islam* means submission, the main concept preached by all prophets.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Quran also mentions God having revealed the Scrolls of Abraham and the Scrolls of Moses.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Islamic tradition claims that twelve Arab tribes known as the Ishmaelites are descended from Abraham through his son Ishmael in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The relationship between Islamic and Hebrew scriptures and New Testament differs significantly from the relationship between the New Testament and the Hebrew Bible.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In the 7th century AD, Islam was founded by Muhammad in the Arabian Peninsula; it spread widely through the early Muslim conquests, shortly after his death.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Islam understands its form of "Abrahamic monotheism" as preceding both Judaism and Christianity, and in contrast with Arabian Henotheism.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The teachings of the Quran are believed by Muslims to be the direct and final revelation and words of God.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Islam, like Christianity, is a universal religion (i.e. membership is open to anyone).
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Like Judaism, it has a strictly unitary conception of God, called *tawhid* or "strict monotheism".
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The story of the creation of the world in the Quran is elaborated less extensively than in the Hebrew scripture, emphasizing the transcendence and universality of God, instead.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] According to the Quran, God says *kun fa-yakūnu*.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Quran describes God as the creator of "heavens and earth", to emphasize that it is a universal God and not a local Arabian deity.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Samaritanism is considered by some fringe Jewish and Christian apologetics to be a sect which diverged from Judaism in the 6th to 3rd centuries BCE.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] There is growing archaeological, DNA testing, and textual evidence in modern times which has proved the status of the Israelite Samaritans as an independent Abrahamic ethnoreligion and indigenous people of the Levant in their own right.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The evidence has authenticated their claim to a legal religious status.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Some sources consider Mandaeism to be an Abrahamic religion – however, that classification is controversial, given that Mandaeism does not accept Abraham as a prophet, despite revering as prophets several other figures from the Jewish scriptures.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] On the contrary, the Mandaeans believe that Abraham was originally a priest of their religion, but became an apostate from it.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Druze is another religion which emerged from Islam in the 11th century, and hence is sometimes also considered an Abrahamic religion.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Yazidism, another Kurdish religion, is considered a syncretic religion and shares elements with Shia Islam, Mandaeism, Christianity, and Judaism, including a belief in Adam and Abraham.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] It has also been influenced by Islamic mysticism and Gnostic Christianity.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In Yazidism, the prophet Abraham is invoked during prayers before a meal, especially ritual meals.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] A number of sources include the Baháʼí Faith, established in the 19th century, since it historically emerged in an Islamic milieu, and shares several beliefs with the Abrahamic faiths, including monotheism and recognising Jewish, Christian and Islamic figures as prophets.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Some scholars include Bábism, a 19th-century movement and precursor to the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Rastafari, an Afrocentric religion which emerged from Christianity in 1930s Jamaica, is also sometimes classified as Abrahamic, in particular due to its monotheism and use of the Bible as scripture.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Abrahamic religions agree upon the createdness of the universe by God, who is conceived of as eternal, omnipotent, and omniscient.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] All three identify the creator of the universe with the God revealed to Abraham.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] However, they differ on how to conceptualize God.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Christianity proposes God's utter transcendence and that an intermediary — such as an incarnation of God — is required to bridge the gap between God and humans.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] According to Islam, God is knowable through his creation, metaphorical stories of the prophets stored in the Quran, and signs in nature.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Christianity proposes God's personhood in the form of a Son of God as an aspect of the Divinity as formulated in the doctrine of the Trinity.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In contrast, God in Islam is less personal than described in the Judeo-Christian tradition, and more of a mysterious power behind all aspects of the universe.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Their religious texts feature many of the same figures, histories, and places, although they often present them with different roles, perspectives, and meanings.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Believers who agree on these similarities and the common Abrahamic origin tend to also be more positive towards other Abrahamic groups.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Religious law in Judaism and Samaritanism commands that males be circumcised when they are eight days old, as does the *sunnah* ('tradition') in Islam.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Despite its common practice in Muslim-majority nations, circumcision is considered to be *sunnah* and not required for a life directed by Allah.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Although there is some debate within Islam over whether it is a religious requirement or mere recommendation, circumcision (called *khitan*) is practiced nearly universally by Muslim males.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Today, many Christian denominations are neutral about ritual male circumcision, neither requiring it for religious observance nor forbidding it for cultural or other reasons.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Western Christianity replaced the custom of male circumcision with the ritual of baptism, a ceremony which varies according to the doctrine of the denomination, but it generally includes immersion, aspersion, or anointment with water.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Early Church, as recorded in Acts 15 at the Council of Jerusalem, decided that Gentile Christians are not required to undergo circumcision.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Council of Florence in the 15th century prohibited it.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Paragraph #2297 of the Catechism of the Catholic Church calls non-medical amputation or mutilation immoral.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] By the 21st century, the Catholic Church had adopted a neutral position on the practice, as long as it was not practised as an initiation ritual.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Catholic scholars make various arguments in support of the idea that this policy is not in contradiction with the previous edicts.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The New Testament, in Acts 15, records that Christianity did not require circumcision.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Coptic Christians practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Eritrean Orthodox Church and the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church calls for circumcision, with near-universal prevalence among Orthodox men in Ethiopia.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Many countries with majorities of Christian adherents in Europe and Latin America have low circumcision rates.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In contrast, both religious and non-religious circumcision is widely practiced in many predominantly Christian countries and among Christian communities in the Anglosphere countries, Oceania, South Korea, the Philippines, the Middle East and Africa.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Countries such as the United States, the Philippines, Australia (albeit primarily in the older generations), Canada, Cameroon, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Equatorial Guinea, Ghana, Nigeria, Kenya, and many other African Christian countries have high circumcision rates.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Circumcision is near universal in the Christian countries of Oceania.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In some African and Eastern Christian denominations male circumcision is an integral or established practice, and require that their male members undergo circumcision.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Coptic Christianity and Ethiopian Orthodoxy and Eritrean Orthodoxy still observe male circumcision and practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Male circumcision is also widely practiced among Christians from Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Palestine, Israel, and North Africa.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Male circumcision is among the rites of Islam and is part of the *fitrah*, or the innate disposition and natural character and instinct of the human creation.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Although circumcision is widely practiced among the Druze, it is performed as a cultural tradition and has no religious significance in the Druze faith.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Some Druze do not circumcise their male children, and refuse to observe this "common Muslim practice".
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Circumcision is not a religious practice of the Bahá'í Faith, and the decision is left to the parents.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Judaism accepts converts, but has had no explicit missionaries since the end of the Second Temple period.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Judaism states that non-Jews can achieve righteousness by following Noahide Laws, a set of moral imperatives that, according to the Talmud, were given by God as a binding set of laws for the "children of Noah"—that is, all of humanity.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] It is believed that as much as 10% of the Roman Empire followed Judaism either as fully ritually obligated Jews or the simpler rituals required of non-Jewish members of that faith.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In the U.S., as of 2003, 28% of married Jews were married to non-Jews.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Many Christian organizations, especially Protestant churches, send missionaries to non-Christian communities throughout the world.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions to Catholicism have happened at various points throughout history.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions to Protestantism has occurred as well, notably during the Reformation, especially in England and Ireland (see recusancy and Popish plot).
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions are now condemned as sinful by major denominations such as the Roman Catholic Church, which officially states that forced conversions pollute the Christian religion and offend human dignity, so that past or present offences are regarded as a scandal (a cause of unbelief).
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] According to Pope Paul VI, "It is one of the major tenets of Catholic doctrine that man's response to God in faith must be free: no one, therefore, is to be forced to embrace the Christian faith against his own will." The Roman Catholic Church has declared that Catholics should fight anti-Semitism.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Islam encourages proselytism in various forms.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Dawah is an important Islamic concept that denotes the preaching of Islam.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Da‘wah literally means "issuing a summons" or "making an invitation".
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] A Muslim who practices da‘wah, either as a religious worker or in a volunteer community effort, is called a dā‘ī, plural du‘āt.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] A dā‘ī is thus a person who invites people to understand Islam through a dialogical process and may be categorized in some cases as the Islamic equivalent of a missionary, as one who invites people to the faith, to the prayer, or to Islamic life.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Some pursue Islamic studies specifically to perform Da'wah.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Mosques and other Islamic centers sometimes actively spread Da'wah, similar to evangelical churches.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Others consider being open to the public and answering questions to be Da'wah.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Recalling Muslims to the faith and expanding their knowledge can also be considered Da'wah.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] In Islamic theology, the purpose of Da'wah is to invite people, both Muslims and non-Muslims, to understand the commandments of God as expressed in the Quran and the Sunnah of the Prophet, as well as to inform them about Muhammad.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Da'wah produces converts to Islam, which in turn grows the size of the Muslim Ummah, or community of Muslims.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] While there were instances of forced conversions to Islam, these were neither the norm nor part of a systematic strategy of expansion.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Many Muslim rulers practiced religious pluralism, and the Quran explicitly prohibits compulsion in matters of faith.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Most conversions to Islam occurred gradually, driven by social, cultural, and economic influences rather than coercion.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] However, forcible conversion continues to be practiced in parts of the Islamic world.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Christianity is the largest Abrahamic religion with about 2.5 billion adherents, called Christians, constituting about 31.1% of the world's population.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] Islam is the second largest Abrahamic religion, as well as the fastest-growing Abrahamic religion in recent decades.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] It has about 2.0 billion adherents, called Muslims, constituting about 24.1% of the world's population.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The third largest Abrahamic religion is Judaism with about 14.1 million adherents, called Jews.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Baháʼí Faith has over 8 million adherents, making it the fourth largest Abrahamic religion, and the fastest growing religion across the 20th century, usually at least twice the rate of population growth.
[src:death/abrahamic-religions] The Druze faith has between one million and nearly two million adherents.
[src:death/death] Many cultures and religions have a concept of an afterlife.
[src:death/death] The study of death is known as thanatology.
[src:death/death] As of the early 21st century, 56 million people die per year.
[src:death/death] As of 2022, an estimated total of almost 110 billion humans have died, or roughly 94% of all humans to have ever lived.
[src:death/death] The cause of death is usually considered important, and an autopsy can be done to determine it.
[src:death/death] There are many causes, from accidents to diseases or crime and war.
[src:death/death] The most common reason is aging; the most common cause is cardiovascular disease (CVD), which is a disease that affects the heart or blood vessels.
[src:death/death] A substudy of gerontology known as biogerontology seeks to eliminate death by natural aging in humans, often through the application of natural processes found in certain organisms.
[src:death/death] However, as humans do not have the means to apply this to themselves, they have to use other ways to reach the maximum lifespan for a human, often through lifestyle changes, such as calorie reduction, dieting, and exercise.
[src:death/death] The idea of lifespan extension is considered and studied as a way for people to live longer.
[src:death/death] Determining when a person has definitively died has proven difficult.
[src:death/death] Initially, death was defined as occurring when breathing and the heartbeat ceased, a status still known as clinical death.
[src:death/death] However, the development of cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) meant that such a state was no longer strictly irreversible.
[src:death/death] For all organisms with a brain, death can instead be focused on this organ.
[src:death/death] Brain death is sometimes used as a legal definition of death.
[src:death/death] There are different customs for honoring the lifeless body, such as a funeral, cremation, or sky burial.
[src:death/death] After a death, an obituary may be posted in a newspaper, and the family and friends of the dead person usually go through the grieving process.
[src:death/death] There are many scientific approaches and various interpretations of the concept.
[src:death/death] Additionally, the advent of life-sustaining therapy and the numerous criteria for defining death from both a medical and legal standpoint have made it difficult to create a single unifying definition.
[src:death/death] One of the challenges in defining death is in distinguishing it from life.
[src:death/death] As a point in time, death seems to refer to the moment when life ends.
[src:death/death] Determining when death has occurred is difficult, as cessation of life functions is often not simultaneous across organ systems.
[src:death/death] Such determination, therefore, requires drawing precise conceptual boundaries between life and death.
[src:death/death] This is difficult due to there being little consensus on how to define life.
[src:death/death] It is possible to define life in terms of consciousness.
[src:death/death] When consciousness ceases, an organism can be said to have died.
[src:death/death] One of the flaws in this approach is that there are many organisms that are alive but probably not conscious.
[src:death/death] Another problem is in defining consciousness, which has many different definitions given by modern scientists, psychologists and philosophers.
[src:death/death] Additionally, many religious traditions, including Abrahamic and Dharmic traditions, hold that death does not (or may not) entail the end of consciousness.
[src:death/death] In certain cultures, death is more of a process than a single event.
[src:death/death] It implies a slow shift from one spiritual state to another.
[src:death/death] Other definitions for death focus on the character of cessation of organismic functioning and human death, which refers to irreversible loss of personhood.
[src:death/death] More specifically, death occurs when a living entity experiences irreversible cessation of all functioning.
[src:death/death] As it pertains to human life, death is an irreversible process where someone loses their existence as a person.
[src:death/death] Historically, attempts to define the exact moment of a human's death have been subjective or imprecise.
[src:death/death] Death was defined as the cessation of heartbeat (cardiac arrest) and breathing, but the development of CPR and prompt defibrillation have rendered that definition inadequate because breathing and heartbeat can sometimes be restarted.
[src:death/death] This type of death where circulatory and respiratory arrest happens is known as the circulatory definition of death (CDD).
[src:death/death] Proponents of the CDD believe this definition is reasonable because a person with permanent loss of circulatory and respiratory function should be considered dead.
[src:death/death] Critics of this definition state that while cessation of these functions may be permanent, it does not mean the situation is irreversible because if CPR is applied fast enough, the person could be revived.
[src:death/death] Thus, the arguments for and against the CDD boil down to defining the actual words "permanent" and "irreversible," which further complicates the challenge of defining death.
[src:death/death] Furthermore, events causally linked to death in the past no longer kill in all circumstances; without a functioning heart or lungs, life can sometimes be sustained with a combination of life support devices, organ transplants, and artificial pacemakers.
[src:death/death] Today, where a definition of the moment of death is required, doctors and coroners usually turn to "brain death" or "biological death" to define a person as being dead; people are considered dead when the electrical activity in their brain ceases.
[src:death/death] It is presumed that an end of electrical activity indicates the end of consciousness.
[src:death/death] Suspension of consciousness must be permanent and not transient, as occurs during certain sleep stages, and especially a coma.
[src:death/death] In the case of sleep, electroencephalograms (EEGs) are used to tell the difference.
[src:death/death] The category of "brain death" is seen as problematic by some scholars.
[src:death/death] While "brain death" is viewed as problematic by some scholars, there are proponents of it that believe this definition of death is the most reasonable for distinguishing life from death.
[src:death/death] The reasoning behind the support for this definition is that brain death has a set of criteria that is reliable and reproducible.
[src:death/death] Also, the brain is crucial in determining our identity or who we are as human beings.
[src:death/death] The distinction should be made that "brain death" cannot be equated with one in a vegetative state or coma, in that the former situation describes a state that is beyond recovery.
[src:death/death] EEGs can detect spurious electrical impulses, while certain drugs, hypoglycemia, hypoxia, or hypothermia can suppress or even stop brain activity temporarily; because of this, hospitals have protocols for determining brain death involving EEGs at widely separated intervals under defined conditions.
[src:death/death] One view is that the neocortex of the brain is necessary for consciousness, and that therefore only electrical activity of the neocortex should be considered when defining death.
[src:death/death] Eventually, the criterion for death may be the permanent and irreversible loss of cognitive function, as evidenced by the death of the cerebral cortex.
[src:death/death] All hope of recovering human thought and personality is then gone, given current and foreseeable medical technology.
[src:death/death] Even by whole-brain criteria, the determination of brain death can be complicated.
[src:death/death] There is a more conservative definition of death: irreversible cessation of all functions of the whole brain, as opposed to just in the neo-cortex.
[src:death/death] One example is the Uniform Determination Of Death Act in the United States.
[src:death/death] In the past, the adoption of this whole-brain definition was a conclusion of the President's Commission for the Study of Ethical Problems in Medicine and Biomedical and Behavioral Research in 1980.
[src:death/death] They concluded that this approach to defining death sufficed in reaching a uniform definition nationwide.
[src:death/death] A multitude of reasons was presented to support this definition, including uniformity of standards in law for establishing death, consumption of a family's fiscal resources for artificial life support, and legal establishment for equating brain death with death to proceed with organ donation.
[src:death/death] Aside from the issue of support of or dispute against brain death, there is another inherent problem in this categorical definition: the variability of its application in medical practice.
[src:death/death] In 1995, the American Academy of Neurology (AAN) established the criteria that became the medical standard for diagnosing neurologic death.
[src:death/death] At that time, three clinical features had to be satisfied to determine "irreversible cessation" of the total brain, including coma with clear etiology, cessation of breathing, and lack of brainstem reflexes.
[src:death/death] These criteria were updated again, most recently in 2010, but substantial discrepancies remain across hospitals and medical specialties.
[src:death/death] The death of a person has legal consequences that may vary between jurisdictions.
[src:death/death] Most countries follow the whole-brain death criteria, where all functions of the brain must have completely ceased.
[src:death/death] However, in other jurisdictions, some follow the brainstem version of brain death.
[src:death/death] Afterward, a death certificate is issued in most jurisdictions, either by a doctor or by an administrative office, upon presentation of a doctor's declaration of death.
[src:death/death] A great deal of controversy has surrounded the definition of death and the dead donor rule.
[src:death/death] Advocates of the rule believe that the rule is legitimate in protecting organ donors while also countering any moral or legal objection to organ procurement.
[src:death/death] Critics, on the other hand, believe that the rule does not uphold the best interests of the donors and that the rule does not effectively promote organ donation.
[src:death/death] The leading cause of human death in developing countries is infectious disease.
[src:death/death] The leading causes in developed countries are atherosclerosis (heart disease and stroke), cancer, and other diseases related to obesity and aging.
[src:death/death] By an extremely wide margin, the largest unifying cause of death in the developed world is biological aging, leading to various complications known as aging-associated diseases.
[src:death/death] These conditions cause loss of homeostasis, leading to cardiac arrest, causing loss of oxygen and nutrient supply, causing irreversible deterioration of the brain and other tissues.
[src:death/death] Of the roughly 150,000 people who die each day across the globe, about two thirds die of age-related causes.
[src:death/death] In industrialized nations, the proportion is much higher, approaching 90%.
[src:death/death] With improved medical capability, dying has become a condition to be managed.
[src:death/death] In developing nations, inferior sanitary conditions and lack of access to modern medical technology make death from infectious diseases more common than in developed countries.
[src:death/death] One such disease is tuberculosis, a bacterial disease that killed 1.8 million people in 2015.
[src:death/death] In 2004, malaria caused about 2.7 million deaths annually.
[src:death/death] The AIDS death toll in Africa may reach 90–100 million by 2025.
[src:death/death] According to Jean Ziegler, the United Nations Special Reporter on the Right to Food from 2000 to March 2008, mortality due to malnutrition accounted for 58% of the total mortality rate in 2006.
[src:death/death] Ziegler says worldwide, approximately 62 million people died from all causes and of those deaths, more than 36 million died of hunger or diseases due to deficiencies in micronutrients.
[src:death/death] Tobacco smoking killed 100 million people worldwide in the 20th century and could kill 1 billion people worldwide in the 21st century, a World Health Organization report warned.
[src:death/death] Many leading developed world causes of death can be postponed by diet and physical activity, but the accelerating incidence of disease with age still imposes limits on human longevity.
[src:death/death] The evolutionary cause of aging is, at best, only beginning to be understood.
[src:death/death] It has been suggested that direct intervention in the aging process may now be the most effective intervention against major causes of death.
[src:death/death] Selye proposed a unified non-specific approach to many causes of death.
[src:death/death] He demonstrated that stress decreases the adaptability of an organism and proposed to describe adaptability as a special resource in itself, *adaptation energy*.
[src:death/death] The animal dies when this resource is exhausted.
[src:death/death] Selye assumed that adaptability is a finite supply presented at birth.
[src:death/death] But later, Goldstone proposed the concept of production or income of adaptation energy which may be stored (up to a limit) as a capital reserve of adaptation.
[src:death/death] In recent works, adaptation energy is considered an internal coordinate on the "dominant path" in the model of adaptation.
[src:death/death] It is demonstrated that oscillations of well-being appear when the reserve of adaptability is almost exhausted.
[src:death/death] In 2012, suicide overtook car crashes as the leading cause of human injury deaths in the U.S., followed by poisoning, falls, and murder.
[src:death/death] Accidents and disasters, from nuclear disasters to structural collapses, also claim lives.
[src:death/death] One of the deadliest incidents of all time is the 1975 Banqiao Dam Failure, with varying estimates, up to 240,000 dead.
[src:death/death] Other incidents with high death tolls are the Wanggongchang explosion (when a gunpowder factory ended up with 20,000 deaths), a collapse of a wall of Circus Maximus that killed 13,000 people, and the Chernobyl disaster that killed between 95 and 4,000 people.
[src:death/death] Natural disasters kill around 45,000 people annually, although this number can vary from thousands to millions on a per-decade basis.
[src:death/death] If naturally occurring famines are considered natural disasters, the Chinese famine of 1906–1907, which killed 15–20 million people, can be considered the deadliest natural disaster in recorded history.
[src:death/death] In animals, predation can be a common cause of death.
[src:death/death] Livestock have a 6% death rate from predation.
[src:death/death] However, younger animals are more susceptible to predation.
[src:death/death] For example, 50% of young foxes die to birds, bobcats, coyotes, and other foxes as well.
[src:death/death] Young bear cubs in the Yellowstone National Park only have a 40% chance to survive to adulthood from other bears and predators.
[src:death/death] An autopsy, also known as a *postmortem examination* or an *obduction*, is a medical procedure that consists of a thorough examination of a human corpse to determine the cause and manner of a person's death and to evaluate any disease or injury that may be present.
[src:death/death] It is usually performed by a specialized medical doctor called a pathologist.
[src:death/death] Autopsies are either performed for legal or medical purposes.
[src:death/death] A forensic autopsy is carried out when the cause of death may be a criminal matter, while a clinical or academic autopsy is performed to find the medical cause of death and is used in cases of unknown or uncertain death, or for research purposes.
[src:death/death] Autopsies can be further classified into cases where external examination suffices, and those where the body is dissected and an internal examination is conducted.
[src:death/death] Permission from next of kin may be required for internal autopsy in some cases.
[src:death/death] Once an internal autopsy is complete the body is generally reconstituted by sewing it back together.
[src:death/death] A necropsy, which is not always a medical procedure, was a term previously used to describe an unregulated postmortem examination.
[src:death/death] In modern times, this term is more commonly associated with the corpses of animals.
[src:death/death] There are many anecdotal references to people being declared dead by physicians and then "coming back to life," sometimes days later in their coffin or when embalming procedures are about to begin.
[src:death/death] From the mid-18th century onwards, there was an upsurge in the public's fear of being mistakenly buried alive and much debate about the uncertainty of the signs of death.
[src:death/death] Various suggestions were made to test for signs of life before burial, ranging from pouring vinegar and pepper into the corpse's mouth to applying red hot pokers to the feet or into the rectum.
[src:death/death] Ouseley claimed that as many as 2,700 people were buried prematurely each year in England and Wales, although some estimates peg the figure to be closer to 800.
[src:death/death] In cases of electric shock, cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) for an hour or longer can allow stunned nerves to recover, allowing an apparently dead person to survive.
[src:death/death] People found unconscious under icy water may survive if their faces are kept continuously cold until they arrive at an emergency room.
[src:death/death] This "diving response," in which metabolic activity and oxygen requirements are minimal, is something humans share with cetaceans called the mammalian diving reflex.
[src:death/death] The lack of electrical brain activity may not be enough to consider someone scientifically dead.
[src:death/death] Therefore, the concept of information-theoretic death has been suggested as a better means of defining when true death occurs, though the concept has few practical applications outside the field of cryonics.
[src:death/death] Death before birth can happen in several ways: stillbirth, when the fetus dies before or during the delivery process; miscarriage, when the embryo dies before independent survival; and abortion, the artificial termination of the pregnancy.
[src:death/death] Stillbirth and miscarriage can happen for various reasons, while abortion is carried out purposely.
[src:death/death] Stillbirth can happen right before or after the delivery of a fetus.
[src:death/death] It can result from defects of the fetus or risk factors present in the mother.
[src:death/death] Reductions of these factors, caesarean sections when risks are present, and early detection of birth defects have lowered the rate of stillbirth.
[src:death/death] However, 1% of births in the United States end in a stillbirth.
[src:death/death] There are many risk-factors involved in miscarriage; consumption of caffeine, tobacco, alcohol, drugs, having a previous miscarriage, and the use of abortion can increase the chances of having a miscarriage.
[src:death/death] An abortion may be performed for many reasons, such as pregnancy from rape, financial constraints of having a child, teenage pregnancy, and the lack of support from a significant other.
[src:death/death] There are two forms of abortion: a medical abortion and an in-clinic abortion or sometimes referred to as a surgical abortion.
[src:death/death] Almost all animals who survive external hazards to their biological functioning eventually die from biological aging, known in life sciences as "senescence." Some organisms experience negligible senescence, even exhibiting biological immortality.
[src:death/death] These include the jellyfish *Turritopsis dohrnii*, the hydra, and the planarian.
[src:death/death] Unnatural causes of death include suicide and predation.
[src:death/death] Of all causes, roughly 150,000 people die around the world each day.
[src:death/death] Of these, two-thirds die directly or indirectly due to senescence, but in industrialized countries – such as the United States, the United Kingdom, and Germany – the rate approaches 90% (i.e., nearly nine out of ten of all deaths are related to senescence).
[src:death/death] Physiological death is now seen as a process, more than an event: conditions once considered indicative of death are now reversible.
[src:death/death] Where in the process, a dividing line is drawn between life and death depends on factors beyond the presence or absence of vital signs.
[src:death/death] In general, clinical death is neither necessary nor sufficient for a determination of legal death.
[src:death/death] A patient with working heart and lungs determined to be brain dead can be pronounced legally dead without clinical death occurring.
[src:death/death] Life extension refers to an increase in maximum or average lifespan, especially in humans, by slowing or reversing aging processes through anti-aging measures.
[src:death/death] Aging is the most common cause of death worldwide.
[src:death/death] Aging is seen as inevitable, so according to Aubrey de Grey little is spent on research into anti-aging therapies, a phenomenon known as pro-aging trance.
[src:death/death] The average lifespan is determined by vulnerability to accidents and age or lifestyle-related afflictions such as cancer or cardiovascular disease.
[src:death/death] Extension of lifespan can be achieved by good diet, exercise, and avoidance of hazards such as smoking.
[src:death/death] Maximum lifespan is determined by the rate of aging for a species inherent in its genes.
[src:death/death] A recognized method of extending maximum lifespan is calorie restriction.
[src:death/death] Theoretically, the extension of the maximum lifespan can be achieved by reducing the rate of aging damage, by periodic replacement of damaged tissues, molecular repair, or rejuvenation of deteriorated cells and tissues.
[src:death/death] A United States poll found religious and irreligious people, as well as men and women and people of different economic classes, have similar rates of support for life extension, while Africans and Hispanics have higher rates of support than white people.
[src:death/death] 38% said they would desire to have their aging process cured.
[src:death/death] Researchers of life extension can be known as "biomedical gerontologists." They try to understand aging, and develop treatments to reverse aging processes, or at least slow them for the improvement of health and maintenance of youthfulness.
[src:death/death] Those who use life extension findings and apply them to themselves are called "life extensionists" or "longevists." The primary life extension strategy currently is to apply anti-aging methods to attempt to live long enough to benefit from a cure for aging.
[src:death/death] Cryonics (from Greek κρύος 'kryos-' meaning 'icy cold') is the low-temperature preservation of animals, including humans, who cannot be sustained by contemporary medicine, with the hope that healing and resuscitation may be possible in the future.
[src:death/death] Cryopreservation of people and other large animals is not reversible with current technology.
[src:death/death] The stated rationale for cryonics is that people who are considered dead by current legal or medical definitions, may not necessarily be dead according to the more stringent 'information-theoretic' definition of death.
[src:death/death] Some scientific literature is claimed to support the feasibility of cryonics.
[src:death/death] Medical science and cryobiologists generally regard cryonics with skepticism.
[src:death/death] Death studies is a field within psychology.
[src:death/death] To varying degrees people inherently fear death, both the process and the eventuality; it is hard wired and part of the 'survival instinct' of all animals.
[src:death/death] Discussing, thinking about, or planning for their deaths causes them discomfort.
[src:death/death] This fear may cause them to put off financial planning, preparing a will and testament, or requesting help from a hospice organization.
[src:death/death] Mortality salience is the awareness that death is inevitable.
[src:death/death] However, self-esteem and culture are ways to reduce the anxiety this effect can cause.
[src:death/death] The awareness of someone's own death can cause a deepened bond in their in-group as a defense mechanism.
[src:death/death] This can also cause the person to become very judging.
[src:death/death] In a study, two groups were formed; one group was asked to reflect upon their mortality, the other was not, afterwards, the groups were told to set a bond for a prostitute.
[src:death/death] The group that did not reflect on death had an average of $50, the group who was reminded about their death had an average of $455.
[src:death/death] Different people have different responses to the idea of their deaths.
[src:death/death] Philosopher Galen Strawson writes that the death that many people wish for is an instant, painless, unexperienced annihilation.
[src:death/death] In this unlikely scenario, the person dies without realizing it and without being able to fear it.
[src:death/death] One moment the person is walking, eating, or sleeping, and the next moment, the person is dead.
[src:death/death] Strawson reasons that this type of death would not take anything away from the person, as he believes a person cannot have a legitimate claim to ownership in the future.
[src:death/death] In society, the nature of death and humanity's awareness of its mortality has, for millennia, been a concern of the world's religious traditions and philosophical inquiry.
[src:death/death] This includes belief in resurrection or an afterlife (associated with Abrahamic religions), reincarnation or rebirth (associated with Dharmic religions), or that consciousness permanently ceases to exist, known as eternal oblivion (associated with secular humanism).
[src:death/death] Commemoration ceremonies after death may include various mourning, funeral practices, and ceremonies for honoring the deceased.
[src:death/death] The physical remains of a person, commonly known as a *corpse* or *body*, are usually interred whole or cremated, though among the world's cultures, there are a variety of other methods of mortuary disposal.
[src:death/death] In the English language, blessings directed towards a dead person include *rest in peace* (originally the Latin, *requiescat in pace*) or its initialism RIP.
[src:death/death] Death is the center of many traditions and organizations; customs relating to death are a feature of every culture around the world.
[src:death/death] Much of this revolves around the care of the dead, as well as the afterlife and the disposal of bodies upon the onset of death.
[src:death/death] The disposal of human corpses does, in general, begin with the last offices before significant time has passed, and ritualistic ceremonies often occur, most commonly interment or cremation.
[src:death/death] This is not a unified practice; in Tibet, for instance, the body is given a sky burial and left on a mountain top.
[src:death/death] Proper preparation for death and techniques and ceremonies for producing the ability to transfer one's spiritual attainments into another body (reincarnation) are subjects of detailed study in Tibet.
[src:death/death] Mummification or embalming is also prevalent in some cultures to retard the rate of decay.
[src:death/death] The rise of secularism resulted in material mementos of death declining.
[src:death/death] Some parts of death in culture are legally based, having laws for when death occurs, such as the receiving of a death certificate, the settlement of the deceased estate, and the issues of inheritance and, in some countries, inheritance taxation.
[src:death/death] Capital punishment is also a culturally divisive aspect of death.
[src:death/death] In most jurisdictions where capital punishment is carried out today, the death penalty is reserved for premeditated murder, espionage, treason, or as part of military justice.
[src:death/death] In some countries, sexual crimes, such as adultery and sodomy, carry the death penalty, as do religious crimes, such as apostasy, the formal renunciation of one's religion.
[src:death/death] In many retentionist countries, drug trafficking is also a capital offense.
[src:death/death] In China, human trafficking and serious cases of corruption are also punished by the death penalty.
[src:death/death] In militaries around the world, courts-martial have imposed death sentences for offenses such as cowardice, desertion, insubordination, and mutiny.
[src:death/death] Mutiny is punishable by death in the United States.
[src:death/death] Death in warfare and suicide attacks also have cultural links, and the ideas of *dulce et decorum est pro patria mori,* which translates to "It is sweet and proper to die for one's country", is a concept that dates to antiquity.
[src:death/death] Additionally, grieving relatives of dead soldiers and death notification are embedded in many cultures.
[src:death/death] Suicide, in general, and particularly euthanasia, are also points of cultural debate.
[src:death/death] Both acts are understood very differently in different cultures.
[src:death/death] In Japan, for example, ending a life with honor by seppuku was considered a desirable death, whereas according to traditional Christian and Islamic cultures, suicide is viewed as a sin.
[src:death/death] Death is personified in many cultures, with such symbolic representations as the Grim Reaper, Azrael, the Hindu god Yama, and Father Time.
[src:death/death] In western cultures, the Grim Reaper, or figures similar to it, is the most popular depiction of death.
[src:death/death] In Brazil, death is counted officially when it is registered by existing family members at a cartório, a government-authorized registry.
[src:death/death] Before being able to file for an official death, the deceased must have been registered for an official birth at the cartório.
[src:death/death] Though a Public Registry Law guarantees all Brazilian citizens the right to register deaths, regardless of the financial means of their family members (often children), the Brazilian government has not taken away the burden, hidden costs, and fees of filing for a death.
[src:death/death] For many impoverished families, the indirect costs and burden of filing for a death lead to a more appealing unofficial, local, and cultural burial, which in turn raises the debate about inaccurate mortality rates.
[src:death/death] Talking about death and witnessing it is a difficult issue in most cultures.
[src:death/death] Western societies may like to treat the dead with the utmost material respect, with an official embalmer and associated rites.
[src:death/death] Eastern societies like India may be more open to accepting it as a *fait accompli*, with a funeral procession of the dead body ending in an open-air burning-to-ashes.
[src:death/death] Around 1930, most people in Western countries died in their own homes, surrounded by family, and comforted by clergy, neighbors, and doctors making house calls.
[src:death/death] By the mid-20th century, half of all Americans died in a hospital.
[src:death/death] By the start of the 21st century, only about 20 to 25% of people in developed countries died outside of a medical institution.
[src:death/death] The shift from dying at home towards dying in a professional medical environment has been termed the "Invisible Death." This shift occurred gradually over the years, and most deaths now occur outside the home.
[src:death/death] The origin of death is a theme or myth of how death came to be.
[src:death/death] It is present in nearly all cultures across the world, as death is a universal happening.
[src:death/death] This makes it an origin myth, a myth that describes how a feature of the natural or social world appeared.
[src:death/death] There can be some similarities between myths and cultures.
[src:death/death] In North American mythology, the theme of a man who wants to be immortal and a man who wants to die can be seen across many Indigenous people.
[src:death/death] In Christianity, death is the result of the fall of man after eating the fruit from the tree of the knowledge of good and evil.
[src:death/death] In Greek mythology, the opening of Pandora's box releases death upon the world.
[src:death/death] Much interest and debate surround the question of what happens to one's consciousness as one's body dies.
[src:death/death] The belief in the permanent loss of consciousness after death is often called *eternal oblivion*.
[src:death/death] The belief that the stream of consciousness is preserved after physical death is described by the term *afterlife*.
[src:death/death] Near-death experiences (NDEs) describe the subjective experiences associated with impending death.
[src:death/death] Some survivors of such experiences report it as "seeing the afterlife while they were dying".
[src:death/death] Seeing a being of light and talking with it, life flashing before the eyes, and the confirmation of cultural beliefs of the afterlife are common themes in NDEs.
[src:death/death] Many religious traditions regard funeral and end-of-life rituals as important practices that help mark or support an individual's passage from life to afterlife.
[src:death/death] In Buddhist doctrine and practice, death plays an important role.
[src:death/death] Awareness of death motivated Prince Siddhartha to strive to find the "deathless" and finally attain enlightenment.
[src:death/death] In Buddhist doctrine, death functions as a reminder of the value of having been born as a human being.
[src:death/death] Rebirth as a human being is considered the only state in which one can attain enlightenment.
[src:death/death] Therefore, death helps remind oneself that one should not take life for granted.
[src:death/death] The belief in rebirth among Buddhists does not necessarily remove death anxiety since all existence in the cycle of rebirth is considered filled with suffering, and being reborn many times does not necessarily mean that one progresses.
[src:death/death] Death is part of several key Buddhist tenets, such as the Four Noble Truths and dependent origination.
[src:death/death] In Buddhist traditions, preparation for death is regarded as an important aspect of spiritual practice.
[src:death/death] Practitioners are encouraged to contemplate the inevitability of death as a means of developing awareness of the value and rarity of human life.
[src:death/death] Since death is unavoidable and its timing uncertain, individuals are advised to live ethically by avoiding unwholesome actions of body, speech, and mind while cultivating wholesome actions that support spiritual progress and liberation.
[src:death/death] The mental state at the time of death is considered especially significant because it is believed to influence the transition to a future existence.
[src:death/death] According to Buddhist teachings, the final moment of consciousness in one life conditions the first moment of consciousness in the next.
[src:death/death] For this reason, practitioners seek to cultivate calmness, mindfulness, and emotional stability throughout life so that fear, anger, or agitation do not dominate the mind at the moment of death and negatively affect future rebirth.
[src:death/death] While Christian denominations have varying beliefs, they generally agree that all humans are souls, a unity of their physical body and their spirit.
[src:death/death] After one dies, Christians believe that during this time, their spirit would separate from their body, and enter the afterlife.
[src:death/death] Additionally, they hold that when the Second Coming of Jesus occurs, resurrection would follow, and the spirit would be reunified with the body.
[src:death/death] In Hindu texts, death is described as the individual eternal spiritual *jiva-atma* (soul or conscious self) exiting the current temporary material body.
[src:death/death] The soul exits this body when the body can no longer sustain the conscious self (life), which may be due to mental or physical reasons or, more accurately, the inability to act on one's *kama* (material desires).
[src:death/death] During conception, the soul enters a compatible new body based on the remaining merits and demerits of one's *karma* (good/bad material activities based on *dharma*) and the state of one's mind (impressions or last thoughts) at the time of death.
[src:death/death] Usually, the process of reincarnation makes one forget all memories of one's previous life.
[src:death/death] Because nothing really dies and the temporary material body is always changing, both in this life and the next, death means forgetfulness of one's previous experiences.
[src:death/death] The Islamic view is that death is the separation of the soul from the body as well as the beginning of the afterlife.
[src:death/death] The afterlife, or *akhirah,* is one of the six main beliefs in Islam.
[src:death/death] Rather than seeing death as the end of life, Muslims consider death as a continuation of life in another form.
[src:death/death] In Islam, life on earth right now is a short, temporary life and a testing period for every soul.
[src:death/death] True life begins with the Day of Judgement when all people will be divided into two groups.
[src:death/death] The righteous believers will be welcomed to *janna* (heaven), and the disbelievers and evildoers will be punished in *jahannam* (hellfire).
[src:death/death] Muslims believe death to be wholly natural and predetermined by God.
[src:death/death] Only God knows the exact time of a person's death.
[src:death/death] The Quran emphasizes that death is inevitable, no matter how much people try to escape death, it will reach everyone.
[src:death/death] (Q50:16) Life on earth is the one and only chance for people to prepare themselves for the life to come and choose to either believe or not believe in God, and death is the end of that learning opportunity.
[src:death/death] There are a variety of beliefs about the afterlife within Judaism, but none of them contradict the preference for life over death.
[src:death/death] This is partially because death puts a cessation to the possibility of fulfilling any commandments.
[src:death/death] A common human response to death is grief and mourning.
[src:death/death] While it is commonly discussed as an emotion, grief also has physical, cognitive, behavioral, social, cultural, spiritual, political and philosophical aspects.
[src:death/death] The state of being in grief is called "bereavement".
[src:death/death] Death plays a role in extinction, which is generally considered to be the death of the last individual of a species.
[src:death/death] After death, the remains of a former organism become part of the biogeochemical cycle, during which animals may be consumed by a predator or a scavenger.
[src:death/death] Organic material may then be further decomposed by detritivores, organisms that recycle detritus, returning it to the environment for reuse in the food chain, where these chemicals may eventually end up being consumed and assimilated into the cells of an organism.
[src:death/death] Examples of detritivores include earthworms, woodlice, and millipedes.
[src:death/death] Microorganisms also play a vital role, raising the temperature of the decomposing matter as they break it down into yet simpler molecules.
[src:death/death] Not all materials need to be fully decomposed.
[src:death/death] Coal, a fossil fuel formed over vast tracts of time in swamp ecosystems, is one example.
[src:death/death] The contemporary evolutionary theory sees death as an important part of the process of natural selection.
[src:death/death] It is considered that organisms less adapted to their environment are more likely to die, having produced fewer offspring, thereby reducing their contribution to the gene pool.
[src:death/death] Their genes are thus eventually bred out of a population, leading at worst to extinction and, more positively, making the process possible, referred to as speciation.
[src:death/death] Frequency of reproduction plays an equally important role in determining species survival: an organism that dies young but leaves numerous offspring displays, according to Darwinian criteria, much greater fitness than a long-lived organism leaving only one.
[src:death/death] Death also has a role in competition, where if a species out-competes another, there is a risk of death for the population, especially in the case where they are directly fighting over resources.
[src:death/death] Inquiry into the evolution of aging aims to explain why so many living things and the vast majority of animals weaken and die with age.
[src:death/death] However, there are exceptions, such as *Hydra* and the jellyfish *Turritopsis dohrnii*, which research shows to be biologically immortal.
[src:death/death] In multicellular organisms and also in multinucleate ciliates with a Weismannist development, that is, with a division of labor between mortal somatic (body) cells and "immortal" germ (reproductive) cells, death becomes an essential part of life, at least for the somatic line.
[src:death/death] The *Volvox* algae are among the simplest organisms to exhibit that division of labor between two completely different cell types, and as a consequence, include the death of somatic line as a regular, genetically regulated part of its life history.
[src:death/death] Cell death is the event of a biological cell ceasing to carry out its functions.
[src:death/death] This may be the result of the natural process of old cells dying and being replaced by new ones, as in programmed cell death, or may result from factors such as diseases, localized injury, or the death of the organism of which the cells are part.
[src:death/death] Apoptosis or type I cell-death, and autophagy or type II cell-death are both forms of programmed cell death, while necrosis is a non-physiological process that occurs as a result of infection or injury.
[src:death/death] The term "cell necrobiology" has been used to describe the life processes associated with morphological, biochemical, and molecular changes which predispose, precede, and accompany cell death, as well as the consequences and tissue response to cell death.
[src:death/death] The word is derived from the Greek νεκρό meaning "death", βìο meaning "life", and λόγος meaning "the study of".
[src:death/death] The term was initially coined to broadly define investigations of the changes that accompany cell death, detected and measured by multiparameter flow- and laser scanning- cytometry.
[src:death/death] It has been used to describe the real-time changes during cell death, detected by flow cytometry.
[src:death/death] The word "death" comes from Old English *dēaþ*, which in turn comes from Proto-Germanic **dauþuz* (reconstructed by etymological analysis).
[src:death/death] The concept and symptoms of death, and varying degrees of delicacy used in discussion in public forums, have generated numerous scientific, legal, and socially acceptable terms or euphemisms.
[src:death/death] When a person has died, it is also said they have "passed away", "passed on", "expired", or "gone", among other socially accepted, religiously specific, slang, and irreverent terms.
[src:death/death] As a formal reference to a dead person, it has become common practice to use the participle form of "decease", as in "the deceased"; another noun form is "decedent".
[src:death/death] Bereft of life, the dead person is a "corpse", "cadaver", "body", "set of remains", or when all flesh is gone, a "skeleton".
[src:death/death] The terms "carrion" and "carcass" are also used, usually for dead non-human animals.
[src:death/death] The ashes left after a cremation are lately called "cremains".
